no a wealth of data

00:00:26.010 --> 00:00:29.061
showing that having an
effective gratitude practice

00:00:29.061 --> 00:00:32.880
can impact a huge number
of health variables;

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:36.100
both mental health and physical
health in positive ways.

00:00:36.100 --> 00:00:37.530
Things like cardiovascular health,

00:00:37.530 --> 00:00:40.550
things like relationships,
things like mental health,

00:00:40.550 --> 00:00:42.760
things like physical and
cognitive performance.

00:00:42.760 --> 00:00:44.130
And these are not small effects.

00:00:44.130 --> 00:00:46.910
These are very large positive effects.

00:00:46.910 --> 00:00:48.750
However, in researching this episode,

00:00:48.750 --> 00:00:50.060
I was completely surprised

00:00:50.060 --> 00:00:54.730
as to what constitutes an
effective gratitude practice.

00:00:54.730 --> 00:00:56.800
I, I think like many of
you, would have thought

00:00:56.800 --> 00:00:58.210
that an effective gratitude practice

00:00:58.210 --> 00:01:00.440
simply involves writing down a few things

00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:02.230
or many things that we're grateful for,

00:01:02.230 --> 00:01:03.720
or thinking about those.

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:07.550
Or really making an effort to somaticize

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:10.900
or feel some of the elements of gratitude

00:01:10.900 --> 00:01:13.730
while writing out that list
or thinking about that list.

00:01:13.730 --> 00:01:16.550
It turns out that an
effective gratitude practice

00:01:16.550 --> 00:01:18.330
doesn't resemble that at all.

00:01:18.330 --> 00:01:20.670
The neuroimaging data,
the physiological data,

00:01:20.670 --> 00:01:24.520
looking at things like inflammatory
markers, other studies,

00:01:24.520 --> 00:01:27.020
purely looking at the
psychology and the long

00:01:27.020 --> 00:01:29.960
and short-term effects of an
effective gratitude practice,

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:33.400
point to a completely different
approach to using gratitude

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:35.870
to positively impact health metrics.

00:01:35.870 --> 00:01:36.830
Fortunately, these are things

00:01:36.830 --> 00:01:38.710
that we can all do very easily.

00:01:38.710 --> 00:01:41.070
Some of them were actually fun.

00:01:41.070 --> 00:01:43.000
You can do them in a variety of contexts.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:44.680
So today we're going to
talk about the science

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:46.760
of effective gratitude practices,

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:48.310
and we're going to describe what those are

00:01:48.310 --> 00:01:50.720
and how you can incorporate
them into your life.

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:52.320
Before we dive into today's topic,

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:53.480
I just want to highlight

00:01:53.480 --> 00:01:55.240
a particularly interesting set of findings

00:01:55.240 --> 00:01:56.630
from the literature.

00:01:56.630 --> 00:01:58.990
This is a study that came out
in the journal Cell Report,

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:00.810
Cell Press journal, excellent journal.

00:02:00.810 --> 00:02:02.970
It's very relevant to today's topic.

00:02:02.970 --> 00:02:04.760
In fact, we're going to spend
more time with this paper

00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:06.720
a little bit later in the episode.

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:11.636
The study involved having
subjects listen to a story.

00:02:11.636 --> 00:02:14.810
The subjects are all
listening to the same story,

00:02:14.810 --> 00:02:16.870
but those subjects are not
listening to it together.

00:02:16.870 --> 00:02:19.260
They're not rounded up in
a circle or all in a room,

00:02:19.260 --> 00:02:20.190
they're in separate rooms

00:02:20.190 --> 00:02:23.570
or entirely separate
locations on the planet,

00:02:23.570 --> 00:02:26.180
or they are actually
brought into the laboratory

00:02:26.180 --> 00:02:27.173
on separate days.

00:02:28.010 --> 00:02:31.890
What this study found is
that different subjects

00:02:31.890 --> 00:02:34.000
listening to the same story,

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.683
undergo the same variation in heart rate.

00:02:38.530 --> 00:02:41.180
In other words, the gaps
between their heartbeats

00:02:41.180 --> 00:02:45.020
start to resemble one another
in response to the same story.

00:02:45.020 --> 00:02:46.350
Now, this is very interesting.

00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:50.690
This is a coordination of
the physiology of the body

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:54.600
in response to a narrative,
a story in different people.

00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:57.040
And yet when they line up the heart rates

00:02:57.040 --> 00:02:59.150
of these different people
who listen to the story

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:00.660
at completely different times,

00:03:00.660 --> 00:03:02.060
they find that those heart rates

00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:04.630
map onto one another almost identically.

00:03:04.630 --> 00:03:06.314
It's really remarkable.

00:03:06.314 --> 00:03:08.330
We're going to talk about what this means

00:03:08.330 --> 00:03:11.180
in terms of coordination of
neural circuits in the brain

00:03:11.180 --> 00:03:12.670
and neural circuits in the body,

00:03:12.670 --> 00:03:14.460
and the organs such as the heart,

00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:16.400
but also the lungs and
other organs of the body,

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:20.090
and what this means for
changing one's overall state.

00:03:20.090 --> 00:03:23.170
A key theme that's going to
come up today again and again

00:03:23.170 --> 00:03:25.880
is the distinction between traits,

00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:29.670
which are kind of pervasive
aspects of who we are

00:03:29.670 --> 00:03:30.700
and how we tend to react

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:32.700
to different types of circumstances,

00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:34.810
and states, which are more transient.

00:03:34.810 --> 00:03:37.630
They tend to, you know, you
can invoke a state in somebody,

00:03:37.630 --> 00:03:40.100
a state of fear or a state of relaxation.

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:42.620
But what this study
really starts to point to

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:44.350
is that there are specific approaches

00:03:44.350 --> 00:03:45.740
that any of us can take

00:03:45.740 --> 00:03:48.690
in order to really rewire
our nervous system,

00:03:48.690 --> 00:03:51.530
such that we are calmer,
if we want to be calmer

00:03:51.530 --> 00:03:52.930
in certain circumstances,

00:03:52.930 --> 00:03:55.610
that we are more responsive
in certain circumstances,

00:03:55.610 --> 00:03:56.670
if that's our goal.

00:03:56.670 --> 00:03:58.870
So we'll return to how one
would go about doing that.

00:03:58.870 --> 00:04:01.570
But I think these results
are just beautiful

00:04:01.570 --> 00:04:03.350
in the sense that they really show

00:04:03.350 --> 00:04:05.420
that our brain and our
body are highly coordinated

00:04:05.420 --> 00:04:06.607
because people are listening to the story

00:04:06.607 --> 00:04:10.360
and the heart rate is changing
in response to the story,

00:04:10.360 --> 00:04:14.270
but that there is what
we call a stereotypy;

00:04:14.270 --> 00:04:17.600
sort of stereotyped
response to a given story.

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:18.790
In my mind, there was no reason

00:04:18.790 --> 00:04:20.610
why the results had to be this way.

00:04:20.610 --> 00:04:21.990
Two people listen to the same story,

00:04:21.990 --> 00:04:23.900
why should their heart
rates be almost identical

00:04:23.900 --> 00:04:25.010
to the same story?

00:04:25.010 --> 00:04:28.020
Very, very interesting and
points to the power of narrative

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:30.950
and story in coordinating our physiology.

00:04:30.950 --> 00:04:33.030
And this is something
powerful that we can leverage.

